<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The nation's economy will continue to expand in 1989 but growth will slow 
slightly, according to a report by a panel of economists sponsored by the 
Conference Board. The group projected that real gross national product will 
rise about 2.5% this year, down from about 2.7% in 1988. The group also 
projected that inflation would rise to 5% from 4.2%, the prime rate would hold 
steady at about 10.5% and unemployment would increase slightly to 5.5%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- ECONOMY; ECONOMIC FORECASTS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021089-0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 16574 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 10, 1989, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
