<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIMES WRITER WINS 1988 DIRKSEN AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sara Fritz, The Times' congressional correspondent, Wednesday was named the 
winner of the Everett McKinley Dirksen Award for the best reporting on Congress 
during 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Fritz won the $5,000 award, bestowed by the Dirksen Congressional Center, for a 
series of four articles titled "What's Wrong with Congress," that ran from Jan. 
24 to Jan. 27, 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Fritz has worked in the Times Washington Bureau since 1983. The Dirksen 
Congressional Center, based in Pekin, Ill., is a nonpartisan, nonprofit 
research and educational institution named after the late Republican senator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
REPORTERS; AWARDS; FRITZ, SARA; LOS ANGELES TIMES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
