<HEADLINE>
<P>
CASE CLOSED IN CLEMSON PLAYERS' BRAWL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COLUMBIA, S.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Solicitor Joe Watson said today that no criminal charges will be filed in a 
fight involving several Clemson basketball players and two campus security 
guards. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to submit it to the grand jury," Watson said in a telephone 
interview from his office in Greenville. "It's over as far as a criminal 
investigation." 
</P>
<P>
Saying that both sides share the blame for the fight, Watson added that the 
security guards acted "unprofessionally," cursing at and chasing the students 
after police arrived. He said the two security guards eventually had to be 
subdued by police. 
</P>
<P>
The fight occurred Jan. 21 in the parking lot of an apartment complex that 
serves as the basketball players' dormitory. Watson declined to identify the 
players involved, but sources said 6-foot, 11-inch junior center Elden Campbell 
was among those who took part in the fight. 
</P>
<P>
The two Crowe's Inc. security guards involved in the fight suffered minor 
injuries. The fight, which Watson said lasted two or three minutes, occurred 
shortly after Clemson downed Western Carolina at Littlejohn Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
"It was basically a case where both sides acted immaturely. Basically, there 
were aggravating points on both sides," Watson said. "I'm not pointing blame at 
any one of them." 
</P>
<P>
The fight prompted the Clemson Police Department to ask for help from the State 
Law Enforcement Division. Watson said that probably neither he nor the state 
officers would have been involved in the investigation had athletes not been 
involved in the fight. 
</P>
<P>
"That was the thing that made it bigger than it was, because some Clemson 
athletes were involved," he said. "The Police Department wanted someone who was 
independent to look at their findings." 
</P>
<P>
Watson said statements were taken from 20 to 25 people during the probe, which 
took longer than expected because those involved initially lied about what 
happened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
